         <div type="commentary">
            <head>Commentary</head>
            <p>After c, may be there was a index of Gods. </p>
            <p>This document, unfortunately fragmentary and not precisely connected with any
                    building, is apparently a formal instruction concerned with the proper and
                    respectful organisation of pagan cults (<foreign xml:lang="grc">θρησκεία</foreign>
                    in fr. a. - on the sense see line  Robert, <title level="m">Études d'Épigraphie et Philologie</title>, p.
                    226 f.) perhaps after desecration (<foreign xml:lang="grc">πλημμελουμεν<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
               </foreign>
                    in fr. a., for the sense see line  Robert, line c. p. 143); probably purification (cf.
                    <foreign xml:lang="grc">καθαιρειται</foreign> in fr. c.) as well as expiatory
                    offerings were involved (<foreign xml:lang="grc">ἱλάσκεσθαι</foreign> in fr. a.).
                    The <foreign xml:lang="grc">συνωμοσίαι</foreign> of fr. b. are obscure.</p>
            <p>An obvious occasion for such a measure would be the Jewish Revolt of C.E. 115,
                    but the lettering looks too late; a roman inroad in the third or
                    fourth century would provide an alternative.</p>
         </div>
         
